<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1174&amp;p=20250#p20250"><![CDATA[
Now that I think of it, try desoldering pin 22 from one of the connectors.  That'd be a good place to start.  It's an address input to the NES's internal VRAM.  Some carts will connect it directly to either PPU-A10 or PPU-A11 (to select the mirroring mode).  Others, like SMB3, can control what it's connected to through software with it's mapper.  It's almost certain there'll be a conflict there.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Mon Dec 11, 2006 5:36 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
