<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1174&amp;p=20243#p20243"><![CDATA[
Ok so i know this is an old thread but i want to bring life back into it with a new project i have embarked on and to now have yet to fail but yeaterday i hit a critical point int he project where i needed to get to a point to find out if my theory was correct and of course it was not so now im stuck. <br /><br />I started with my old nes dissasembled and some 24 gauge copper wire<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/01.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/07.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/08.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />next i took my power/reset board and examined it to see what i needed to do <br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/02.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />i decided i wanted to have a remote power/reset button and other features.<br />so i soldered 4 wires 2 to each switch for now<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/05.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />since i am going to be porting out about 10-20 wires i decided to use an already implemented connection. I used a parallel printer cable jack. I wanted it in the front of the nes but not over the buttons or the controller ports so it had to go in the center but its length would not fit because of the center peg for the bottom screw holding the top on. not wanting to hurt the integrity of the case i opted to turn the jack sideways.<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/03.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/04.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />this next image shows everything in place with connections made<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/06.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />next i decided to diable the lockout chip. i was originally going to connect pin 4 of the cic lockout chip to a ground but in desoldering it i broke it off which is ok unless you plan to play gold games such as zelda whcih i just have hated all my life with a passion and i dont know why.<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/10.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/09.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />your soldering iron is the best friend in a project like this so invest in something that will be with you in the long run i use a digital soldering station with ground termination for the equipment your working on you know you dont want to kill any components. components run at minimal voltage &lt;6volts and any static can damage IC's and other parts.<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/11.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />after a while your sponge may become lost or too dirty then i would suggest buying some o-cello sponges from your local dollar store and cut one to fit your tray<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/12.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />my extra hands help out in some situations<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/15.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />my fan helps suck the dangerous fumes away when soldering<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/16.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />there are alot of wires your dealing with here so pay attention and dont mix them up. remeber 72 pins minus the expansion ports leaves alot of wires. the wire im using was a bulk phone company wire with 50 wires inside so chopped off two 2 foot sections and used them. as for the soldering you get the idea in the next few pictures<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/14.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/18.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/19.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/20.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />now i was planning on soldering 8 connectors to the main feed so about 65 wires in a series all connected except for pin 36 which is +5v for the nes cart. my theory was that cutting power would stop interferences from the other game carts. well i had to get the main connector and two more connectors on in order to test this. once i was done i tested it.<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/21.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/22.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/23.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />so i power on my nes with mario bros 3 and donkey kong plugged in power only to mario and it looks fine at first but notice the bottom of the screen there are a series of m's and other characters<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/24.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />then when the title screen shows up its all messed up<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/25.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />so i power off remove donkey kong and power back on and voila its back to normal<br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/26.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://www.twistedfantasies.com/NES/27.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />so i dont know what to do next in my quest to run 8 games in a solely hardware switched system<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=1795">tomass</a> — Sun Dec 10, 2006 10:02 pm</p><hr />
