<div class="quotetitle">pragma wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Then I figure a lot of bus driver chips.<br /></div><br /><br />Here's where I'm out of my depth; If you could kindly fill me in (or point me to a good tutorial as I'd like to learn more), I'd appreciate it.<br /></div><br /><br />Well I've never built anything like this, I just have the designs in my head, heheh.  I was looking at using the 74HCT245 for a similar use.  Have something like that for every data bus of every slot (using the read/write signal to select the direction), and possibly another similar chip that's not bidirectional (if it's cheaper or whatever) for all the address and control signals.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Also, I noticed in the pictures on the sites I posted at the top of this thread, that there was a ceramic cap for each set of chips on the 'massive multicart board'.  Do you think that was being done to filter out irregularities in the power (between+5V and GND), or something else?  Would that be something to bring into this design as well?<br /></div><br /><br />Definitely yeah, have a .1uF cap connected to directly to VCC and GND of each chip whenever possible.   The cap powers the chip when it needs it.  CMOS chips only uses much power when changing states, the cap will handle the little sudden power demand.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Interesting idea.  How would you insert the active cart-switching software into the works without it tripping all over what games are plugged in?<br /></div><br /><br />Just copy the code into RAM, and run it from there.  Kinda like bankswitching, but more like cartswitching, heheh.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Wed Mar 01, 2006 12:55 pm</p><hr />
