<div class="quotetitle">teaguecl wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Q is very right on this, I learned the hard way.  Look for some of my old topics if you want details on the fiasco I had getting 72 pin connectors.  I have resorted to buying the "U" shaped replacement connectors off ebay, and doing some serious re-work on them with a Dremel.  This produces a very usable connector, but is a lot of work, and mechanically not as nice as a vertically mounted card edge connector would be.<br /></div><br /><br />This is what I get for not searching the forums in the first place.  Teaguecl, your posts on that other thread was pivotal in learning about how hard it is to mimic that part.  Its either do this, or do what Ben Heckendorn did and hack up some floppy connectors.  I've seen other folks chop up an old ISA connector too, but the pitch (2.54) makes it impractical to mate with the whole cartridge edge, as you've already noted.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />If only I could figure out where the clone makers like Messiah get their parts.  A call to their office revealed that they have no idea... the device is designed and manufactured in Asia, the guys in LA know almost nothing about it.<br /></div><br /><br />If only!<br /><br />Probably the same place all the other famiclone manufacturers are getting their parts from - maybe there's some discrete cache of them somewhere, tucked away in a black-market warehouse, off some back-alley in Hong-Kong.  <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_sad.gif" alt=":(" title="Sad" /><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=273">pragma</a> — Wed Mar 01, 2006 12:04 pm</p><hr />
