<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1174&amp;p=10239#p10239"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Sorry, but that's no good. The pin pitch is listed as 0.125" (3.18mm), which is WAY too wide for an NES cartridge, whose pitch is 2.50mm.<br /></div><br /><br />Thanks!  My mistake here was assuming that the NES pin pitch was something close to an already established standard - boy was I wrong.  I dug around on the board here and it seems those connectors are hard to come by.  Googling the hell out of the internet to find a suitable replacement hasn't turned up much either.<br /><br />Apparently, the 2.54mm pitch doesn't work 100% either, so only the true 2.5mm ones will do.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />They do have a 60-pin cart edge connector which has 0.100" (2.54mm) pitch, the correct spacing for a Famicom cartridge. However, it is designed for board thicknesses between 0.054" and 0.070"; Famicom cartridge boards are 0.043" thick, so they would fit extremely loosely and might not make consistent contact.<br /></div><br /><br />So I need to find a 2.5mm pitch connector, 72 pins, that will seat a 0.043" board.  I did find <a href="http://www.lumberg.com/Produkte/PDFs/2_5.pdf" class="postlink">this incredibly close match</a> but it seems to be too wide for a good contact.  Also, I can't find any distributors for that part anyway - I put in an inquiry for a discrete order just for grins.<br /><br />Somehow, cutting down replacement toaster-NES connectors seems like the only way forward, as was mentioned... elsewhere (can't remember where though)*.<br /><br />*Edit: it was here, see post below.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=273">pragma</a> — Wed Mar 01, 2006 11:57 am</p><hr />
