<div class="quotetitle">Quietust wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">pragma wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I did my homework on this.  I'm not 100% sure on the dimensions, but this looks like the right connector for a GamePak:<br /><br /><a href="http://www.mouser.com/index.cfm?handler=displayproduct&amp;lstdispproductid=473351&amp;e_categoryid=50&amp;e_pcodeid=58700" class="postlink">EDAC 72P cartridge connector</a><br /><br />At least they ship in (somewhat) discrete quantities.  The price could be lower, but its worth not having to hack ISA or Floppy connectors all afternoon.<br /></div><br /><br />Sorry, but that's no good. The pin pitch is listed as 0.125" (3.18mm), which is WAY too wide for an NES cartridge, whose pitch is 2.50mm.<br /></div><br /><br />Q is very right on this, I learned the hard way.  Look for some of my old topics if you want details on the fiasco I had getting 72 pin connectors.  I have resorted to buying the "U" shaped replacement connectors off ebay, and doing some serious re-work on them with a Dremel.  This produces a very usable connector, but is a lot of work, and mechanically not as nice as a vertically mounted card edge connector would be.  If only I could figure out where the clone makers like Messiah get their parts.  A call to their office revealed that they have no idea... the device is designed and manufactured in Asia, the guys in LA know almost nothing about it.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=29">teaguecl</a> — Wed Mar 01, 2006 11:47 am</p><hr />
