<div class="quotetitle">Memblers wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I had an idea for something like this a while back, just imagining though.  I don't know how much the connectors would cost, probably too much since it's a custom type.<br /></div><br /><br />I did my homework on this.  I'm not 100% sure on the dimensions, but this looks like the right connector for a GamePak:<br /><br /><a href="http://www.mouser.com/index.cfm?handler=displayproduct&amp;lstdispproductid=473351&amp;e_categoryid=50&amp;e_pcodeid=58700" class="postlink">EDAC 72P cartridge connector</a><br /><br />At least they ship in (somewhat) discrete quantities.  The price could be lower, but its worth not having to hack ISA or Floppy connectors all afternoon.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Then I figure a lot of bus driver chips.<br /></div><br /><br />Here's where I'm out of my depth; If you could kindly fill me in (or point me to a good tutorial as I'd like to learn more), I'd appreciate it.   <br /><br />I figured that there might be some problems with capacitance, resistance, or something else with all that unpowered circuitry hanging off of the cartridge lines - but I'm just not educated enough to know for sure.<br /><br />Also, I noticed in the pictures on the sites I posted at the top of this thread, that there was a ceramic cap for each set of chips on the 'massive multicart board'.  Do you think that was being done to filter out irregularities in the power (between+5V and GND), or something else?  Would that be something to bring into this design as well?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Maybe I'm just crazy, but I'd want the thing fully powered (externally) and possibly under control so the program could select any cart whenever it wants.  That'd be a hell of a hardware expansion usable by whatever fits in the NES's internal 2kB of RAM (well, depending on what carts are connected anyways, getting to be like a PC with infinite hardware configs).<br /></div><br /><br />Interesting idea.  How would you insert the active cart-switching software into the works without it tripping all over what games are plugged in?<br /><br />I can see the value in external power, but only if you were powering all the cartridges at once.  Once you've done that, all the chips in every cart could/would respond to activity on the address and data lines, so you'd have to effectively route/switch each cartridge independently.  That would make for one hell of a soldering job.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Also, with just cutting off the power of a cart to disable it (or just ICs in general), is that safe to do electrically?  I was wondering about that for some other designs.  Since the inputs would be getting voltage while VCC and GND are both 0V, a lot of chips will say things like max VCC+0.6V.  It makes the voltage difference sound unsafe, but I don't know.<br /></div><br /><br />Oh, I see: logic typically runs closer to +1.0V, so that's almost double what the rated input would be.  I was hoping that as long as the chips in question had a proper ground, it could tolerate the situation.   <br /><br />And I suppose under-running all the 'dormant' games at VCC+0.5V, or reducing logic to the same would be just as bad.  So using active logic for *each cart* might be the only way to go - so much for keeping it simple. <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_sad.gif" alt=":(" title="Sad" /><br /><br />Given that probably nobody reading this has access to an M82 demo unit, does anyone here know how the Game Genie handles this for one cartridge?  (I'd dismantle one myself if I owned one)<br /><br />Edit: fixed link and spelling.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=273">pragma</a> — Wed Mar 01, 2006 8:19 am</p><hr />
